
[1]option

   OP'TION, n. [L. optio, from opto, to wish or desire.]

   1. The power of choosing; the right of choice or election; as the
   archbishop's option in collating to a vacant benefice.

   There is an option left to the United States of America, whether they
   will be respectable and prosperous, or contemptible and miserable, as a
   nation.

   2. The power of wishing; wish.

   3. Choice; election; preference. He ought not to complain of his lot;
   it was his own option. We leave this to your own option.
